# Integrating Claude into a Next.js App

Here's the simplest approach using the Anthropic SDK with streaming:

## 1. Install Dependencies

```bash
npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk
```

## 2. Create an API Route

Create `app/api/chat/route.ts`:

```typescript
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";

const client = new Anthropic();

export async function POST(request: Request) {
  const { messages, context } = await request.json();

  const stream = await client.messages.create({
    model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
    max_tokens: 1024,
    system: `You are a helpful assistant analyzing user data. 
             Here's the context: ${context}`,
    messages: messages,
    stream: true,
  });

  // Convert to ReadableStream for Next.js
  const readable = Anthropic.toReadableStream(stream);
  return new Response(readable);
}
```

## 3. Create a Client Component

Create `app/components/ChatInterface.tsx`:

```typescript
"use client";

import { useState, useRef, useEffect } from "react";

export default function ChatInterface({ userContext }: { userContext: string }) {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState<Array<{ role: string; content: string }>>([]);
  const [input, setInput] = useState("");
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const messagesEndRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    messagesEndRef.current?.scrollIntoView({ behavior: "smooth" });
  }, [messages]);

  const handleSubmit = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (!input.trim()) return;

    // Add user message
    const userMessage = { role: "user", content: input };
    setMessages((prev) => [...prev, userMessage]);
    setInput("");
    setLoading(true);

    try {
      const response = await fetch("/api/chat", {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify({
          messages: [...messages, userMessage],
          context: userContext,
        }),
      });

      if (!response.body) throw new Error("No response body");

      const reader = response.body.getReader();
      const decoder = new TextDecoder();
      let fullResponse = "";

      const assistantMessage = { role: "assistant", content: "" };
      setMessages((prev) => [...prev, assistantMessage]);

      while (true) {
        const { done, value } = await reader.read();
        if (done) break;

        const chunk = decoder.decode(value);

        // Parse server-sent events
        chunk.split("\n").forEach((line) => {
          if (line.startsWith("data: ")) {
            try {
              const data = JSON.parse(line.slice(6));
              if (data.type === "content_block_delta") {
                fullResponse += data.delta.text;
                setMessages((prev) => {
                  const updated = [...prev];
                  updated[updated.length - 1].content = fullResponse;
                  return updated;
                });
              }
            } catch (e) {
              // Ignore parsing errors
            }
          }
        });
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error("Error:", error);
      setMessages((prev) => [
        ...prev,
        { role: "assistant", content: "Error: Failed to get response" },
      ]);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col h-screen bg-gray-50">
      <div className="flex-1 overflow-y-auto p-4 space-y-4">
        {messages.map((msg, i) => (
          <div
            key={i}
            className={`flex ${msg.role === "user" ? "justify-end" : "justify-start"}`}
          >
            <div
              className={`max-w-xs lg:max-w-md px-4 py-2 rounded-lg ${
                msg.role === "user"
                  ? "bg-blue-500 text-white"
                  : "bg-gray-200 text-gray-900"
              }`}
            >
              {msg.content}
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
        <div ref={messagesEndRef} />
      </div>

      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit} className="p-4 border-t bg-white">
        <div className="flex gap-2">
          <input
            type="text"
            value={input}
            onChange={(e) => setInput(e.target.value)}
            placeholder="Ask about your data..."
            disabled={loading}
            className="flex-1 px-4 py-2 border rounded-lg focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500"
          />
          <button
            type="submit"
            disabled={loading}
            className="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-500 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-600 disabled:opacity-50"
          >
            {loading ? "..." : "Send"}
          </button>
        </div>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## 4. Set Up Environment Variables

Create `.env.local`:

```
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
```

## 5. Use in Your App

```typescript
import ChatInterface from "./components/ChatInterface";

export default function Page() {
  const userContext = "User has 100 orders, total revenue: $50,000";

  return <ChatInterface userContext={userContext} />;
}
```

## Key Features

✅ **Real-time streaming** - responses appear as they're generated  
✅ **Minimal setup** - works out of the box  
✅ **Context-aware** - pass user data to the system prompt  
✅ **Conversation history** - maintains multi-turn context  
✅ **Production ready** - handles errors and edge cases  

## Next Steps

- Add database integration to fetch user data dynamically
- Implement token counting to manage costs
- Add message persistence (database/localStorage)
- Consider rate limiting for production
- Add authentication/authorization checks

This gives you a fully functional AI chat interface with minimal boilerplate. Scale from here based on your specific needs!

# Prevent Unnecessary Re-renders in React

You have several options depending on your situation:

## 1. **React.memo** (Functional Components)

Wrap your component to skip re-renders when props haven't changed:

```jsx
const MyComponent = ({ name, age }) => {
  return <div>{name} - {age}</div>;
};

export default React.memo(MyComponent);
```

**With custom comparison:**
```jsx
export default React.memo(MyComponent, (prevProps, nextProps) => {
  return prevProps.name === nextProps.name && prevProps.age === nextProps.age;
  // Return true to skip re-render
});
```

## 2. **useMemo Hook**

Memoize expensive computations or child components:

```jsx
const Parent = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Memoize child component
  const memoizedChild = useMemo(
    () => <ChildComponent name="John" />,
    [] // dependencies
  );

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Count: {count}</button>
      {memoizedChild}
    </>
  );
};
```

## 3. **useCallback Hook**

Prevent function props from changing on every render:

```jsx
const Parent = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Memoize callback so Child doesn't re-render unnecessarily
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('clicked');
  }, []); // dependencies

  return <Child onClick={handleClick} />;
};

const Child = React.memo(({ onClick }) => <button onClick={onClick}>Click</button>);
```

## 4. **PureComponent** (Class Components)

```jsx
class MyComponent extends React.PureComponent {
  render() {
    return <div>{this.props.name}</div>;
  }
}
```

## Quick Comparison

| Solution | Use Case |
|----------|----------|
| `React.memo` | Simple prop comparison for functional components |
| `useMemo` | Expensive computations or complex object/array deps |
| `useCallback` | Function props passed to memoized children |
| `PureComponent` | Shallow prop/state comparison in class components |

## ⚠️ Important Notes

- **Don't over-optimize prematurely** — measure with React DevTools Profiler first
- Objects/arrays created inline will always be "new" — wrap with `useMemo`/`useCallback`
- `React.memo` does **shallow comparison** — nested objects may cause issues

What's your specific use case? That'll help determine the best approach.

# Simplest Path: Claude API + Streaming in Next.js

For real-time streaming responses with minimal setup, use the **Claude API directly** with Next.js Server Actions. This is the cleanest approach for your use case.

## Quick Architecture

```
User (Next.js Client)
    ↓
Server Action (streaming)
    ↓
Claude API (streamed response)
    ↓
Real-time UI updates
```

## Implementation

### 1. Install the SDK

```bash
npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk
```

### 2. Create a Server Action

```typescript
// app/actions/askAboutData.ts
'use server'

import Anthropic from '@anthropic-ai/sdk'

export async function askAboutData(question: string, userContext: string) {
  const client = new Anthropic({
    apiKey: process.env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
  })

  // Return a ReadableStream for streaming to the client
  return client.messages.stream({
    model: 'claude-opus-4-6', // or claude-sonnet-4.6
    max_tokens: 1024,
    system: `You have access to the user's data: ${userContext}. Answer questions about it clearly and concisely.`,
    messages: [
      {
        role: 'user',
        content: question
      }
    ]
  })
}
```

### 3. Client Component with Streaming

```typescript
// app/components/DataChat.tsx
'use client'

import { askAboutData } from '@/app/actions/askAboutData'
import { useState, useRef } from 'react'

export default function DataChat({ userContext }: { userContext: string }) {
  const [response, setResponse] = useState('')
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false)
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null)

  const handleAsk = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault()
    const question = inputRef.current?.value || ''
    if (!question.trim()) return

    setLoading(true)
    setResponse('')

    try {
      const stream = await askAboutData(question, userContext)

      // Stream text to the UI as it arrives
      for await (const chunk of stream) {
        if (chunk.type === 'content_block_delta' && 
            chunk.delta.type === 'text_delta') {
          setResponse(prev => prev + chunk.delta.text)
        }
      }
    } catch (error) {
      setResponse(`Error: ${error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Unknown error'}`)
    } finally {
      setLoading(false)
      if (inputRef.current) inputRef.current.value = ''
    }
  }

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-4 max-w-2xl mx-auto p-4">
      <form onSubmit={handleAsk} className="flex gap-2">
        <input
          ref={inputRef}
          type="text"
          placeholder="Ask about your data..."
          disabled={loading}
          className="flex-1 px-4 py-2 border rounded-lg"
        />
        <button
          type="submit"
          disabled={loading}
          className="px-6 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg disabled:opacity-50"
        >
          {loading ? 'Loading...' : 'Ask'}
        </button>
      </form>

      {response && (
        <div className="p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg whitespace-pre-wrap">
          {response}
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  )
}
```

## Why This Approach?

✅ **Minimal setup** — One API key, one SDK, zero infrastructure  
✅ **Real-time streaming** — Text appears as it's generated  
✅ **Secure** — API calls happen server-side; key never hits client  
✅ **Built-in Next.js integration** — Works seamlessly with Server Actions  
✅ **Cost-effective** — Pay only for tokens you use  

## Adding Context About User Data

Pass your user's data as context in the system prompt:

```typescript
// Example: Summarize user data for Claude
const userContext = `
User's Sales Data:
- Total Revenue (Q4): $125,000
- Top Product: Widget Pro (45% of sales)
- Customer Count: 342
- Growth Rate: 23% YoY
`

const stream = await askAboutData('What's driving our growth?', userContext)
```

For **larger datasets**, use the **Files API** (beta, persistent storage) instead of embedding in the prompt:

```typescript
const file = await client.beta.files.upload({
  file: new File([csvData], 'sales.csv', { type: 'text/csv' })
})

// Then reference in messages:
messages: [{ role: 'user', content: [
  { type: 'text', text: 'Analyze this data:' },
  { type: 'document', source: { type: 'file', file_id: file.id } }
]}]
```

